  "prompt": "Are there specific laws targeting money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are specific laws targeting money laundering in many countries. In the United States, key anti-money laundering (AML) laws include:\n\n1. Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandates record-keeping and reporting requirements\n\n2. Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Criminalized money laundering as a federal offense\n- Established penalties for individuals and organizations\n\n3. USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Enhanced AML regulations\n- Increased reporting and monitoring requirements\n- Strengthened collaboration between financial institutions and law enforcement\n\nInternationally, organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) set global standards and recommendations for combating money laundering.\n\nThese laws typically:\n- Require financial institutions to conduct customer due diligence\n- Mandate reporting of suspicious transactions\n- Establish criminal penalties for money laundering activities\n- Create mechanisms for tracking and preventing financial crimes\n\nPenalties can include significant fines, asset seizure, and criminal prosecution.\n\nCompliance with these laws is monitored by regulatory agencies like the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) in the United States.",
